# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: next-gen-sequencing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:next-gen-sequencing/coverage-genetics] Even though the sequencing accuracy for each individual nucleotide is very high, the very large number of nucleotides in the genome means that if an individual genome is only sequenced once, there will be a significant number of sequencing errors.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/coverage-genetics] Furthermore, many positions in a genome contain rare single-nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs).
[src:next-gen-sequencing/coverage-genetics] Hence to distinguish between sequencing errors and true SNPs, it is necessary to increase the sequencing accuracy even further by sequencing individual genomes a large number of times.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/coverage-genetics] The term "ultra-deep" can sometimes also refer to higher coverage (>100-fold), which allows for detection of sequence variants in mixed populations.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/coverage-genetics] In the extreme, error-corrected sequencing approaches such as maximum-depth sequencing can make it so that coverage of a given region approaches the throughput of a sequencing machine, allowing coverages of >108.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/coverage-genetics] Deep sequencing of transcriptomes, also known as RNA-Seq, provides both the sequence and frequency of RNA molecules that are present at any particular time in a specific cell type, tissue or organ.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/coverage-genetics] Counting the number of mRNAs that are encoded by individual genes provides an indicator of protein-coding potential, a major contributor to phenotype.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/coverage-genetics] Improving methods for RNA sequencing is an active area of research both in terms of experimental and computational methods.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/coverage-genetics] The average coverage for a whole genome can be calculated from the length of the original genome (*G*), the number of reads (*N*), and the average read length (*L*) as ${\textstyle N\times L/G}$ .
[src:next-gen-sequencing/coverage-genetics] For example, a hypothetical genome with 2,000 base pairs reconstructed from 8 reads with an average length of 500 nucleotides will have 2× redundancy.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/coverage-genetics] This parameter also enables one to estimate other quantities, such as the percentage of the genome covered by reads (sometimes also called breadth of coverage).
[src:next-gen-sequencing/coverage-genetics] A high coverage in shotgun sequencing is desired because it can overcome errors in base calling and assembly.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/coverage-genetics] The subject of DNA sequencing theory addresses the relationships of such quantities.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/coverage-genetics] Sometimes a distinction is made between *sequence coverage* and *physical coverage*.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/coverage-genetics] Where sequence coverage is the average number of times a base is read, physical coverage is the average number of times a base is read or spanned by mate paired reads.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/coverage-genetics] Producing a truly high-quality *finished* sequence by this definition is very expensive.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/coverage-genetics] Thus, most human "whole genome sequencing" results are *draft sequences* (sometimes above and sometimes below the accuracy defined above).
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] This works in three basic steps: amplify, sequence, and analyze.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] The DNA is fragmented and adapters are added that contain segments that act as reference points during amplification, sequencing, and analysis.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] The modified DNA is loaded onto a flow cell where amplification and sequencing will take place.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] The flow cell contains nanowells that space out fragments and help with overcrowding.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Each nanowell contains oligonucleotides that provide an anchoring point for the adapters to attach.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Once the fragments have attached, a phase called cluster generation begins.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] This step makes about a thousand copies of each fragment of DNA and is done by bridge amplification PCR.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Next, primers and modified nucleotides are washed onto the chip.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] These nucleotides have a reversible fluorescent blocker, so the DNA polymerase can add only one nucleotide at a time onto the DNA fragment.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] After each round of synthesis, a camera takes a picture of the chip.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] A computer determines what base was added by the wavelength of the fluorescent tag and records it for every spot on the chip.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] After each round, non-incorporated molecules are washed away.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] A chemical deblocking step is then used to remove the 3' fluorescent terminal blocking group.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] The process continues until the full DNA molecule is sequenced.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] With this technology, thousands of places throughout the genome are sequenced at once via massive parallel sequencing.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] After the DNA is purified from a genomic sample or cDNA is generated, it needs to be converted into library of fragments, genomic library, that can then be sequenced on the instrument.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] This typically involves two key steps: DNA fragmentation, and end repair & adapter ligation.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] There are two ways a genomic library can be fragmented: sonication and tagmentation.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] With tagmentation, modified transposases randomly cut the DNA into sizes between 50 and 500 bp fragments and add adaptors simultaneously.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] A genetic library can also be generated by using sonication to fragment genomic DNA into similar sizes using ultrasonic sound waves.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Specialized adapters are then ligated to the right and left ends of the fragments using T7 DNA Polymerase and T4 DNA ligase.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Strands that fail to have adapters ligated are washed away.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Adapters contain three different segments: the sequence complementary to solid support (oligonucleotides on flow cell), the barcode sequence (indices), and the binding site for the sequencing primer.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Indices are usually six base pairs long and are used during DNA sequence analysis to identify samples.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Indices allow for up to 96 different samples to be run together, this is also known as *multiplexing*.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] During analysis, the computer will group all reads with the same index together.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Illumina uses a "sequence by synthesis" approach.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] This process takes place inside of an acrylamide-coated glass flow cell.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] The flow cell has oligonucleotides (short nucleotide sequences) coating the bottom of the cell, and they serve as the solid support to hold the DNA strands in place during sequencing.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] As the fragmented DNA is washed over the flow cell, the appropriate adapter attaches to the complementary solid support.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Once attached, cluster generation can begin.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] The goal is to create hundreds of identical strands of DNA.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Some will be the forward strand; the rest, the reverse.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] This is why right and left adapters are used.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Clusters are generated through bridge amplification.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] DNA polymerase moves along a strand of DNA, creating its complementary strand.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] The original strand is washed away, leaving only the reverse strand.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] At the top of the reverse strand there is an adapter sequence.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] The DNA strand bends and attaches to the oligo that is complementary to the top adapter sequence.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Polymerases attach to the reverse strand, and its complementary strand (which is identical to the original) is made.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] The now double stranded DNA is denatured so that each strand can separately attach to an oligonucleotide sequence anchored to the flow cell.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] One will be the reverse strand; the other, the forward.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] This process is called bridge amplification, and it happens for thousands of clusters all over the flow cell at once.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Over and over again, DNA strands will bend and attach to the solid support.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] DNA polymerase will synthesize a new strand to create a double stranded segment, and that will be denatured so that all of the DNA strands in one area are from a single source (clonal amplification).
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Clonal amplification is important for quality control purposes.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] If a strand is found to have an odd sequence, then scientists can check the reverse strand to make sure that it has the complement of the same oddity.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] The forward and reverse strands act as checks to guard against artefacts.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Because Illumina sequencing uses DNA polymerase, base substitution errors have been observed, especially at the 3' end.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Paired end reads combined with cluster generation can confirm an error took place.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] The reverse and forward strands should be complementary to each other, all reverse reads should match each other, and all forward reads should match each other.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] If a read is not similar enough to its counterparts (with which it should be a clone), an error may have occurred.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] A minimum threshold of 97% similarity has been used in some labs' analyses.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] At the end of clonal amplification, all of the reverse strands are cleaved at index 2 with a restriction enzyme, and washed off the flow cell, leaving only forward strands.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] A primer attaches to the forward strands adapter primer binding site, and a polymerase adds a fluorescently tagged dNTP to the DNA strand.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Only one base is able to be added per round due to the fluorophore acting as a blocking group; however, the blocking group is reversible.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Using the four-color chemistry, each of the four bases has a unique emission (A=red, G=blue, T=green, C=yellow), and after each round, the machine records which base was added.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Once the color is recorded, the fluorophore is washed away and another dNTP is washed over the flow cell and the process is repeated.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Starting with the launch of the NextSeq and later the MiniSeq, Illumina introduced a new two-color sequencing chemistry.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Nucleotides are distinguished by either one of two colors (red or green), no color ("black") or combining both colors (appearing orange as a mixture between red and green).
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Once the DNA strand has been read, the strand that was just added is washed away.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Then, the index 1 primer attaches, polymerizes the index 1 sequence, and is washed away.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] The strand forms a bridge again, and the 3' end of the DNA strand attaches to an oligo on the flow cell.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] The index 2 primer attaches, polymerizes the sequence, and is washed away.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] A polymerase sequences the complementary strand on top of the arched strand.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] They separate, and the 3' end of each strand is blocked.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] The forward strand cleaved at the index 1 site, and is washed away, and the process of sequence by synthesis repeats for the reverse strand.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] The sequencing occurs for millions of clusters at once, and each cluster has ~1,000 identical copies of a DNA insert.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] The sequence data is analyzed by finding fragments with overlapping areas, called contigs, and lining them up.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] If a reference sequence is known, the contigs are then compared to it for variant identification.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] This piecemeal process allows scientists to see the complete sequence even though an unfragmented sequence was never run; however, because Illumina read lengths are not very long (HiSeq sequencing can produce read lengths around 90 bp long), it can be a struggle to resolve short tandem repeat areas.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Also, if the sequence is de novo and a reference does not exist, repeated areas can cause a lot of difficulty in sequence assembly.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Additional difficulties include base substitutions (especially at the 3' end of reads) by inaccurate polymerases, chimeric sequences, and PCR-bias, all of which can contribute to generating an incorrect sequence.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] This technique offers several advantages over traditional sequencing methods such as Sanger sequencing.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Sanger sequencing requires two reactions, one for the forward primer and another for the reverse primer.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Unlike Illumina, Sanger sequencing uses dideoxynucleoside triphosphates (ddNTPs) to determine the sequence of the DNA fragment. ddNTPs are missing the 3' OH group and terminates DNA synthesis permanently.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] In each reaction tube, dNTPs and ddNTPs are added, along with DNA polymerase and primers.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] The ratio of ddNTPs to dNTPs matter since the template DNA needs to be completely synthesized, and an overabundance of ddNTPs will create multiple fragments of the same size and position of the DNA template.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] When the DNA polymerase adds a ddNTP the fragment is terminated and a new fragment is synthesized.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Each fragment synthesized is one nucleotide longer than the last.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Once the DNA template has been completely synthesized, the fragments are separated by capillary electrophoresis.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] At the bottom of the capillary tube a laser excites the fluorescently labeled ddNTPs and a camera captures the color emitted.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Due to the automated nature of Illumina dye sequencing it is possible to sequence multiple strands at once and gain actual sequencing data quickly.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] With Sanger sequencing, only one strand is able to be sequenced at a time and is relatively slow.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/illumina-dye-sequencing] Illumina only uses DNA polymerase as opposed to multiple, expensive enzymes required by other sequencing techniques (i.e. pyrosequencing).
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Many NGS platforms differ in engineering configurations and sequencing chemistry.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] They share the technical paradigm of massively parallel sequencing via spatially separated, clonally amplified DNA templates or single DNA molecules in a flow cell.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] This design is very different from that of Sanger sequencing—also known as capillary sequencing or first-generation sequencing—which is based on electrophoretic separation of chain-termination products produced in individual sequencing reactions.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] This methodology allows sequencing to be completed on a larger scale.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] In the 1990s, Applied Biosystems dominated DNA sequencing technology with their automated capillary electrophoresis Sanger sequencing machines.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] However, the early 2000s saw many new companies entering the market, driven by the goal of reducing genome sequencing costs below $1000 following the enthusiasm generated by the Human Genome Project.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Many of these new methods were first developed with support from the National Institutes of Health (NIH) funding under the 'Technology Development for the $1,000 Genome' program, launched during Francis Collins’ tenure as director of the National Human Genome Research Institute.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] The first next-generation sequencers were based on pyrosequencing, originally developed by Pyrosequencing AB and later commercialized by 454 Life Sciences.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] In 2003, 454 Life Sciences launched the GS20, the first NGS DNA sequencer.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] This system provided reads approximately 400–500 bp long with 99% accuracy, enabling sequencing of about 25 million bases in a four-hour run at significantly lower costs compared to Sanger sequencing.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] The sequencing machines developed by 454 represented a paradigm shift by enabling the mass parallelisation of sequencing reactions, which significantly boosted the amount of DNA sequenced per run, making 454 Life Sciences the first major success in commercial NGS technology.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Also in 2003, Solexa began developing a competing method known as Sequencing by Synthesis (SBS).
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] In 2004, Solexa acquired colony sequencing (bridge amplification) technology from Manteia, producing densely clustered DNA fragments ("polonies") immobilized on flow cells.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] These dense clusters generated stronger fluorescent signals, improving accuracy and reducing optical costs.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] In 2005, Solexa integrated an engineered DNA polymerase and reversible terminator nucleotides, allowing repeated cycles of sequencing and imaging.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] The first commercial sequencer based on this technology, Genome Analyzer, was launched in 2006, providing shorter reads (about 35 bp) but higher throughput (up to 1 Gbp per run) and paired-end sequencing capability, in which both ends of a DNA fragment are sequenced.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] in 2007, 454 Life Sciences was acquired by Roche and Solexa by Illumina, the same year Applied Biosystems introduced SOLiD, a ligation-based sequencing platform.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] However, SOLiD encountered issues sequencing palindromic regions and was eventually discontinued.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] In 2011, Ion Torrent introduced another alternative, measuring proton (pH) changes during nucleotide incorporation using semiconductor-based sensors.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Ion Torrent systems rapidly produced 100 bp reads but frequently struggled with accurately sequencing homopolymers, ultimately leading to their abandonment.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Due to limitations in competing methods, Illumina’s SBS technology eventually dominated the sequencing market.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] By 2012, expectations that 454 would gain a substantial share of the sequencing market had not been realized, and Roche’s 2007 acquisition was increasingly viewed as underperforming; that same year, Roche made an unsuccessful attempt to acquire Illumina.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] In October 2013, Roche announced that it would shut down 454, and stop supporting the platform by mid-2016.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] By 2014, Illumina controlled approximately 70% of DNA sequencer sales and generated over 90% of sequencing data.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] That year, Illumina introduced the HiSeq X Ten platform, significantly increasing throughput and claiming the long-targeted goal of sequencing human genomes at roughly $1000 each.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Illumina surpassed this milestone in 2017 with the release of NovaSeq, a system capable of generating over 3000 Gbp per run.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Ongoing growth in demand for sequencing data, along with the 2023 expiration of several key Illumina patents, has encouraged a wave of short-read sequencing competitors, each bringing distinct chemistries, flow-cell designs, throughput levels, and cost structures.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] By the early 2020s, Illumina's sequencing-by-synthesis platforms remained dominant; a 2023 overview estimated that more than 90% of the world's sequencing data in 2022 had been generated on Illumina instruments.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Competitors included MGI Tech, whose DNBSEQ platforms use DNA nanoballs rather than Illumina-style bridge amplification, and Ultima Genomics, which developed a production-scale platform using a spinning-disc flow cell.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Singular Genomics introduced the G4 Sequencing Platform in late 2021, Element Biosciences followed by announcing AVITI Sequencing in March 2022, and PacBio later entered the short-read space with its Onso benchtop platform, unveiled in October 2022.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Illumina's NovaSeq X series began shipping in 2023 and used a redesigned flow cell, updated sequencing chemistry, and upgraded optics.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Illumina stated that the system could generate up to three times as much data per run as the previous NovaSeq 6000 and reduce the cost of sequencing a human genome to about US$200 when fully utilized.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] PacBio's involvement in the short-read market was short-lived: after launching the Onso short-read platform in 2023, the company completed the sale of select intellectual property and other assets related to its short-read sequencing technology to Illumina in January 2026.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] DNA sequencing with commercially available NGS platforms is generally conducted with the following steps.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] First, DNA sequencing libraries are generated by clonal amplification by PCR in vitro.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Second, the DNA is sequenced by synthesis, such that the DNA sequence is determined by the addition of nucleotides to the complementary strand rather than through chain-termination chemistry.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Third, the spatially segregated, amplified DNA templates are sequenced simultaneously in a massively parallel fashion without the requirement for a physical separation step.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] These steps are followed in most NGS platforms, but each utilizes a different strategy.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] NGS parallelization of the sequencing reactions generates hundreds of megabases to gigabases of nucleotide sequence reads in a single instrument run.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] This has enabled a drastic increase in available sequence data and fundamentally changed genome sequencing approaches in the biomedical sciences.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Newly emerging NGS technologies and instruments have further contributed to a significant decrease in the cost of sequencing nearing the mark of $500 per genome sequencing in 2022.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] As of 2014, massively parallel sequencing platforms are commercially available and their features are summarized in the table.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] As the pace of NGS technologies is advancing rapidly, technical specifications and pricing are in flux.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Run times and gigabase (Gb) output per run for single-end sequencing are noted.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Run times and outputs approximately double when performing paired-end sequencing. ‡Average read lengths for the Roche 454 and Helicos Biosciences platforms.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Two methods are used in preparing templates for NGS reactions: amplified templates originating from single DNA molecules, and single DNA molecule templates.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] For imaging systems which cannot detect single fluorescence events, amplification of DNA templates is required.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] The three most common amplification methods are emulsion PCR (emPCR), rolling circle and solid-phase amplification.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] The final distribution of templates can be spatially random or on a grid.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] In emulsion PCR methods, a DNA library is first generated through random fragmentation of genomic DNA.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Single-stranded DNA fragments (templates) are attached to the surface of beads with adaptors or linkers, and one bead is attached to a single DNA fragment from the DNA library.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] The surface of the beads contains oligonucleotide probes with sequences that are complementary to the adaptors binding the DNA fragments.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] The beads are then compartmentalized into water-oil emulsion droplets.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] In the aqueous water-oil emulsion, each of the droplets capturing one bead is a PCR microreactor that produces amplified copies of the single DNA template.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Amplification of a population of single DNA molecules by rolling circle amplification in solution is followed by capture on a grid of spots sized to be smaller than the DNAs to be immobilized.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Second-generation sequencing technologies like MGI Tech's DNBSEQ or Element Biosciences' AVITI use this approach for the preparation of the sample on the flow cell that is then imaged cycle by cycle.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Forward and reverse primers are covalently attached at high-density to the slide in a flow cell.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] The ratio of the primers to the template on the support defines the surface density of the amplified clusters.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] The flow cell is exposed to reagents for polymerase-based extension, and priming occurs as the free/distal end of a ligated fragment "bridges" to a complementary oligo on the surface.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Repeated denaturation and extension results in localized amplification of DNA fragments in millions of separate locations across the flow cell surface.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Solid-phase amplification produces 100–200 million spatially separated template clusters, providing free ends to which a universal sequencing primer is then hybridized to initiate the sequencing reaction.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] This technology was filed for a patent in 1997 from Glaxo-Welcome's Geneva Biomedical Research Institute (GBRI), by Pascal Mayer, Eric Kawashima, and Laurent Farinelli, and was publicly presented for the first time in 1998.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] In 1994 Chris Adams and Steve Kron filed a patent on a similar, but non-clonal, surface amplification method, named “bridge amplification” adapted for clonal amplification in 1997 by Church and Mitra.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Protocols requiring DNA amplification are often cumbersome to implement and may introduce sequencing errors.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] The preparation of single-molecule templates is more straightforward and does not require PCR, which can introduce errors in the amplified templates.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] AT-rich and GC-rich target sequences often show amplification bias, which results in their underrepresentation in genome alignments and assemblies.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Single molecule templates are usually immobilized on solid supports using one of at least three different approaches.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] In the first approach, spatially distributed individual primer molecules are covalently attached to the solid support.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] The template, which is prepared by randomly fragmenting the starting material into small sizes (for example,~200–250 bp) and adding common adapters to the fragment ends, is then hybridized to the immobilized primer.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] In the second approach, spatially distributed single-molecule templates are covalently attached to the solid support by priming and extending single-stranded, single-molecule templates from immobilized primers.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] A common primer is then hybridized to the template.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] In either approach, DNA polymerase can bind to the immobilized primed template configuration to initiate the NGS reaction.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Both of the above approaches are used by Helicos BioSciences.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] In a third approach, spatially distributed single polymerase molecules are attached to the solid support, to which a primed template molecule is bound.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] This approach is used by Pacific Biosciences.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Larger DNA molecules (up to tens of thousands of base pairs) can be used with this technique and, unlike the first two approaches, the third approach can be used with real-time methods, resulting in potentially longer read lengths.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] The objective for sequential sequencing by synthesis (SBS) is to determine the sequencing of a DNA sample by detecting the incorporation of a nucleotide by a DNA polymerase.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] An engineered polymerase is used to synthesize a copy of a single strand of DNA and the incorporation of each nucleotide is monitored.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] The principle of sequencing by synthesis was first described in 1993 with improvements published some years later.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Then steps 3-4 are repeated and the sequence is assembled from the signals obtained in step 4.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] This principle of sequencing-by-synthesis has been used for almost all massively parallel sequencing instruments, including 454, PacBio, IonTorrent, Illumina and MGI.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] The principle of Pyrosequencing was first described in 1993 by combining a solid support with an engineered DNA polymerase lacking 3´to 5´exonuclease activity (proof-reading) and luminescence real-time detection using the firefly luciferase.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] This approach uses reversible terminator-bound dNTPs in a cyclic method that comprises nucleotide incorporation, fluorescence imaging and cleavage.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] A fluorescently-labeled terminator is imaged as each dNTP is added and then cleaved to allow incorporation of the next base.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] These nucleotides are chemically blocked such that each incorporation is a unique event.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] An imaging step follows each base incorporation step, then the blocked group is chemically removed to prepare each strand for the next incorporation by DNA polymerase.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] This series of steps continues for a specific number of cycles, as determined by user-defined instrument settings.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] The 3' blocking groups were originally conceived as either enzymatic or chemical reversal The chemical method has been the basis for the Solexa and Illumina machines.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Sequencing by reversible terminator chemistry can be a four-colour cycle such as used by Illumina/Solexa, or a one-colour cycle such as used by Helicos BioSciences.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Helicos BioSciences used “virtual Terminators”, which are unblocked terminators with a second nucleoside analogue that acts as an inhibitor.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] These terminators have the appropriate modifications for terminating or inhibiting groups so that DNA synthesis is terminated after a single base addition.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] In this approach, the sequence extension reaction is not carried out by polymerases but rather by DNA ligase and either one-base-encoded probes or two-base-encoded probes.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] In its simplest form, a fluorescently labelled probe hybridizes to its complementary sequence adjacent to the primed template.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] DNA ligase is then added to join the dye-labelled probe to the primer.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Non-ligated probes are washed away, followed by fluorescence imaging to determine the identity of the ligated probe.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] The cycle can be repeated either by using cleavable probes to remove the fluorescent dye and regenerate a 5′-PO4 group for subsequent ligation cycles (chained ligation) or by removing and hybridizing a new primer to the template (unchained ligation).
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Pacific Biosciences is currently leading this method.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] Pacific Biosciences uses a unique DNA polymerase which better incorporates phospholinked nucleotides and enables the resequencing of closed circular templates.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] While single-read accuracy is 87%, consensus accuracy has been demonstrated at 99.999% with multi-kilobase read lengths.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/massive-parallel-sequencing] In 2015, Pacific Biosciences released a new sequencing instrument called the Sequel System, which increases capacity approximately 6.5-fold.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Nanopore sequencing allows a single molecule of DNA or RNA be sequenced without PCR amplification or chemical labeling.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Nanopore sequencing has the potential to offer relatively low-cost genotyping, high mobility for testing, and rapid processing of samples, including the ability to display real-time results.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] It has been proposed for rapid identification of viral pathogens, monitoring ebola, environmental monitoring, food safety monitoring, human genome sequencing, plant genome sequencing, monitoring of antibiotic resistance, haplotyping and other applications.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Nanopore sequencing took 25 years to materialize.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] David Deamer was one of the first to push the idea.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] In 1989 he sketched out a plan to push single-strands of DNA through a protein nanopore embedded into a thin membrane as part his work to synthesize RNA.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Realizing that the approach might allow DNA sequencing, Deamer and his team spent a decade refining the concept.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] In 1999 they published the first paper using the term 'nanopore sequencing' and two years later produced an image capturing a DNA hairpin passing through a nanopore in real time.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Another foundation for nanopore sequencing was the work of Hagan Bayley's team, who from the 1990s independently developed stochastic sensing, a technique that measures the change in an ionic current passing through a nanopore to determine the concentration and identity of a substance.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] By 2005 Bayley had made progress with the DNA sequencing method.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] He co-founded Oxford Nanopore to push the technology.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] In 2014 the company released its first portable nanopore sequencing device.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] This made it possible for DNA sequencing to be carried out almost anywhere, even with limited resources.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] A quarter of the world's SARS-CoV-2 viral genomes were sequenced with nanopore devices.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The technology offers an important tool for combating antimicrobial resistance.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The biological or solid-state membrane, where the nanopore is found, is surrounded by an electrolyte solution.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The membrane splits the solution into two chambers.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Applying a bias voltage across the membrane induces an electric field that drives charged particles, in this case the ions, into motion.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] This effect is known as electrophoresis.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] For high enough concentrations, the electrolyte solution is well distributed and the voltage drop concentrates near and inside the nanopore.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] This means charged particles in the solution feel a force only from the electric field when they are near the pore region.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] This region is typically referred to as the capture region.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Inside the capture region, ions have a directed motion that can be recorded as a steady ionic current by placing electrodes near the membrane.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] A nano-sized polymer such as DNA or protein placed in one of the chambers has a net charge that feels a force from the electric field in the capture region.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The molecule approaches this capture region aided by Brownian motion.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Any attraction it might have to the surface of the membrane.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Once inside the nanopore, the molecule translocates via a combination of electro-phoretic, electro-osmotic and sometimes thermo-phoretic forces.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Inside the pore the molecule occupies a volume that partially restricts the ion flow, observed as an ionic current drop.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Based on various factors such as geometry, size and chemical composition, the change in magnitude of the ionic current and the duration of the translocation vary.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Different molecules can then be sensed and potentially identified based on this current modulation.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The magnitude of the electric current density across a nanopore surface depends on the nanopore's dimensions and the composition of DNA or RNA that is occupying the nanopore.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Sequencing was made possible because passing through the channel of the nanopore, the samples cause characteristic changes in the density of the electric current.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The total charge flowing through a nanopore channel is equal to the surface integral of electric current density flux across the nanopore unit normal surfaces.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Biological nanopore sequencing relies on the use of transmembrane proteins, called protein nanopores, in particular, formed by protein toxins, that are embedded in lipid membranes so as to create size dependent porous surfaces - with nanometer scale "holes" distributed across the membranes.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Sufficiently low translocation velocity can be attained through the incorporation of various proteins that facilitate the movement of DNA or RNA through the pores of the lipid membranes.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Alpha hemolysin (αHL), a nanopore from bacteria that causes lysis of red blood cells, has been studied for over 15 years.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] To this point, studies have shown that all four bases can be identified using ionic current measured across the αHL pore.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The structure of αHL is advantageous to identify specific bases moving through the pore.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The αHL pore is ~10 nm long, with two distinct 5 nm sections.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The upper section consists of a larger, vestibule-like structure and the lower section consists of three possible recognition sites (R1, R2, R3), and is able to discriminate between each base.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Sequencing using αHL has been developed through basic study and structural mutations, moving towards the sequencing of very long reads.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Protein mutation of αHL has improved the detection abilities of the pore.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The next proposed step is to bind an exonuclease onto the αHL pore.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The enzyme would periodically cleave single bases, enabling the pore to identify successive bases.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Coupling an exonuclease to the biological pore would slow the translocation of the DNA through the pore, and increase the accuracy of data acquisition.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Notably, theorists have shown that sequencing via exonuclease enzymes as described here is not feasible.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] This is mainly due to diffusion related effects imposing a limit on the capture probability of each nucleotide as it is cleaved.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] This results in a significant probability that a nucleotide is either not captured before it diffuses into the bulk or captured out of order, and therefore is not properly sequenced by the nanopore, leading to insertion and deletion errors.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Therefore, major changes are needed to this method before it can be considered a viable strategy.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] A recent study has pointed to the ability of αHL to detect nucleotides at two separate sites in the lower half of the pore.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The R1 and R2 sites enable each base to be monitored twice as it moves through the pore, creating 16 different measurable ionic current values instead of 4.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] This method improves upon the single read through the nanopore by doubling the sites that the sequence is read per nanopore.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Mycobacterium smegmatis porin A (MspA) is the second biological nanopore currently being investigated for DNA sequencing.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The MspA pore has been identified as a potential improvement over αHL due to a more favorable structure.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The pore is described as a goblet with a thick rim and a diameter of 1.2 nm at the bottom of the pore.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] A natural MspA, while favorable for DNA sequencing because of shape and diameter, has a negative core that prohibited single stranded DNA(ssDNA) translocation.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The natural nanopore was modified to improve translocation by replacing three negatively charged aspartic acids with neutral asparagines.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The electric current detection of nucleotides across the membrane has been shown to be tenfold more specific than αHL for identifying bases.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Utilizing this improved specificity, a group at the University of Washington has proposed using double stranded DNA (dsDNA) between each single stranded molecule to hold the base in the reading section of the pore.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The dsDNA would halt the base in the correct section of the pore and enable identification of the nucleotide.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] A 2011 grant was awarded to a collaboration from UC Santa Cruz, the University of Washington, and Northeastern University to improve the base recognition of MspA using phi29 polymerase in conjunction with the pore.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] MspA with electric current detection can also be used to sequence peptides.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The CsgG nanopore is a 36-stranded β-barrel protein from *Escherichia coli*.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The CsgG pore has a nine-fold circular symmetry and a single, well-defined constriction that is approximately 1 nm wide.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] A significant development in its use for sequencing is the creation of a dual-constriction pore by combining CsgG with its partner protein, CsgF.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The N-terminal region of CsgF binds inside the CsgG barrel, creating a second constriction that is roughly 1.5 nm wide and separated from the original CsgG constriction by about 2.5 nm.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] This dual-constriction structure is a major advantage because both constrictions contribute to the electrical signal modulation as a single strand of DNA moves through the pore.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] This dual-reading capability significantly improves sequencing accuracy, particularly for homopolymer regions (stretches of identical bases), which are a known source of errors in nanopore sequencing.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] DNA sequencing using this dual-constriction CsgG:CsgF pore has been shown to improve single-read accuracy by 25-70% in homopolymers up to 9 nucleotides long.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The addition of the second constriction increases the signal complexity, leading to higher accuracy in calling the length of homopolymers compared to a single-constriction CsgG pore.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Solid state nanopore sequencing approaches, unlike biological nanopore sequencing, do not incorporate proteins into their systems.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Instead, solid state nanopore technology uses various metal or metal alloy substrates with nanometer sized pores that allow DNA or RNA to pass through.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] These substrates most often serve integral roles in the sequence recognition of nucleic acids as they translocate through the channels along the substrates.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Measurement of electron tunneling through bases as ssDNA translocates through the nanopore is an improved solid state nanopore sequencing method.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Most research has focused on proving bases could be determined using electron tunneling.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] These studies were conducted using a scanning probe microscope as the sensing electrode, and have proved that bases can be identified by specific tunneling currents.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] After the proof of principle research, a functional system must be created to couple the solid state pore and sensing devices.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Researchers at the Harvard Nanopore group have engineered solid state pores with single walled carbon nanotubes across the diameter of the pore.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Arrays of pores are created and chemical vapor deposition is used to create nanotubes that grow across the array.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Once a nanotube has grown across a pore, the diameter of the pore is adjusted to the desired size.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Successful creation of a nanotube coupled with a pore is an important step towards identifying bases as the ssDNA translocates through the solid state pore.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Another method is the use of nanoelectrodes on either side of a pore.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The electrodes are specifically created to enable a solid state nanopore's formation between the two electrodes.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] This technology could be used to not only sense the bases but to help control base translocation speed and orientation.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Another technique to support ionic current based sensing is called Nanopore electrometry, which has been also recently proposed theoretically.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] This is where the modulations in electric field is utilised instead of the modulations in ionic current for nanopore sensing.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] An effective technique to determine a DNA sequence has been developed using solid state nanopores and fluorescence.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] This fluorescence sequencing method converts each base into a characteristic representation of multiple nucleotides which bind to a fluorescent probe strand-forming dsDNA.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] With the two color system proposed, each base is identified by two separate fluorescences, and will therefore be converted into two specific sequences.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Probes consist of a fluorophore and quencher at the start and end of each sequence, respectively.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Each fluorophore will be extinguished by the quencher at the end of the preceding sequence.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] When the dsDNA is translocating through a solid state nanopore, the probe strand will be stripped off, and the upstream fluorophore will fluoresce.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] This sequencing method has a capacity of 50-250 bases per second per pore, and a four color fluorophore system (each base could be converted to one sequence instead of two), will sequence over 500 bases per second.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Advantages of this method are based on the clear sequencing readout—using a camera instead of noisy current methods.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] However, the method does require sample preparation to convert each base into an expanded binary code before sequencing.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Instead of one base being identified as it translocates through the pore, ~12 bases are required to find the sequence of one base.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Nanopore devices can be used for eDNA analysis in environmental monitoring and crop epidemiology.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] These can be miniaturised more than earlier technologies and so have been made into portable devices, especially the MinION.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The MinION is especially known for the studies of crop viruses by Boykin et al 2018 & Shaffer 2019 and studies of species prevalence by Menegon et al 2017 and Pomerantz et al 2018.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Owing to its high portability, low cost and easiness to use for rapid sequencing applications, it also raised ethical, legal and social concerns along with other next generation sequencing technologies.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] SARS-CoV-2 variants in Prague wastewater were detected by nanopore-based sequencing.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Sequencing of sub-sewershed samples benefits epidemiological early warning systems.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Biological nanopore sequencing systems have several fundamental characteristics that make them advantageous as compared with solid state systems- with each advantageous characteristic of this design approach stemming from the incorporation of proteins into their technology.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Uniform pore structure, the precise control of sample translocation through pore channels, and even the detection of individual nucleotides in samples can be facilitated by unique proteins from a variety of organism types.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The use of proteins in biological nanopore sequencing systems, despite the various benefits, also brings with it some negative characteristics.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The sensitivity of the proteins in these systems to local environmental stress has a large impact on the longevity of the units, overall.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] One example is that a motor protein may only unzip samples with sufficient speed at a certain pH range while not operating fast enough outside of the range- this constraint impacts the functionality of the whole sequencing unit.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Another example is that a transmembrane porin may only operate reliably for a certain number of runs before it breaks down.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Both of these examples would have to be controlled for in the design of any viable biological nanopore system- something that may be difficult to achieve while keeping the costs of such a technology as low and as competitive, to other systems, as possible.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Adaptive sampling can be applied to nanopore sequencing to target or enrich a single gene, reducing the inefficiency and cost associated with whole-genome sequencing.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Functionally, adaptive nanopore sequencing proceeds by the same mechanism as nanopore sequencing, where a single stranded polynucleotide (DNA or RNA) passes through a pore in a sequencing membrane, and characteristic changes in current can be used to identify each base.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] In adaptive sampling, the electrical signal is used in real-time to decode the genome, and a decision is made whether to continue sequencing.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] If the sequence is not of interest, the membrane potential is reversed and the strand is rejected.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Computational processing of the live read must outpace nanopore sequencing, which proceeds at a rate of ~450 nt/s, to provide ample time for decision making.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The two primary modes of adaptive sampling are enrichment and depletion.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] In enrichment mode, regions of interest (ROIs) are supplied.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Each strand is sequenced for a “read-until” decision phase.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Then, if the ROI has not been identified within the sequence, the strand is rejected.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] In depletion mode, however, targets that are not of interest are selected, and a hit leads to rejection.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] This reduces the cost and effort of sequencing contaminants and opens opportunities for improved microbiome metagenome analysis.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Because nanopore sequencing devices can selectively eject DNA strands in real time, they enable fully computational approaches to targeted sequencing.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The success rate of the adaptive nanopore sequencing relies on how instantaneously the computer algorithm can perform.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Oxford Nanopore Technologies provides commercially available nanopore sequencing technology.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] They also produce algorithms for adaptive sequencing, like Guppy and MinKNOW.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Tools such as ReadBouncer enhance the scalability and accuracy of adaptive sampling by quickly determining the nucleotide strand being read.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Further tools, such as AI deep learning or NanoDeep (a Convolutional Neural Network), improve the identification of complex and complicated sequences.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] By using AI to process the electrical signals, these computational methods are capable of sampling multiple ~4000 nucleotide "read-until" steps within milliseconds.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Given these computational advancements, adaptive sampling is capable of outpacing the ~ 450 nt/s procession of the oligonucleotide strand through the pore .
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] While strictly computational targeted sequencing is promising, this results in the need for fast identification of on-target reads.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Additionally, many mapping methods require computationally intensive base calling (the mapping of electrical signal to nucleotide bases).
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] This has resulted in various steps taken such as the open-source mapper UNCALLED which can quickly match nanopore current signals to a reference sequence.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Even though adaptive nanopore sequencing is made more practical by the design of these types of tools, more research is needed to identify false positives / negatives or issues of signal variability .
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Variability in sample composition and sequencing conditions can increase signal noise, and the system software may misinterpret the sequence.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Furthermore, the system has to analyze the signals, make a prediction, and then reach a decision, all in a short time.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Even though the method relies on an advanced computation algorithm, signal variability and sequencing errors can still limit the overall accuracy of the results .
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Adaptive nanopore sequencing can be used to enrich target sequences and cut down on unnecessary sequencing time in long reads.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] When coupled with adaptive sampling, nanopore sequencing has shown to be a reliable and fast long-read sequencing technique, specifically useful in genetic diagnoses of Mendelian diseases.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Because adaptive sequencing enables target enrichment without library preparation steps it has been utilized effectively in a proof-of-concept study investigating structural variants in tumor suppressor genes.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] While breast cancer is not a Mendelian disease, some types are driven by mutations of the BRCA1/2 genes following similar hereditary inheritance.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Adaptive sequencing has produced enrichment of the BRCA1 gene allowing for reduced steps in the sequencing process.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] In “conventional” methods of enrichment, DNA processing steps such as amplification by PCR are required.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] However, avoiding this process altogether reduces cost and improves efficiency.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Overall, this has shown that analyzing pathogenic activity via adaptive nanopore sequencing is a possible method for various tumor suppressor genes. .
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] One challenge for the 'strand sequencing' method was in refining the method to improve its resolution to be able to detect single bases.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] In the early papers methods, a nucleotide needed to be repeated in a sequence about 100 times successively in order to produce a measurable characteristic change.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] This low resolution is because the DNA strand moves rapidly at the rate of 1 to 5μs per base through the nanopore.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] This makes recording difficult and prone to background noise, failing in obtaining single-nucleotide resolution.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] Various techniques including algorithmic have been used to improve the performance of the MinION technology since it was first made available to users.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] More recently effects of single bases due to secondary structure or released mononucleotides have been shown.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] In 2010 Hagan Bayley proposed that creating two recognition sites within an alpha-hemolysin pore may confer advantages in base recognition.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] As of 2009, one challenge for the 'exonuclease approach', where a processive enzyme feeds individual bases, in the correct order, into the nanopore, has been to integrate the exonuclease and the nanopore detection systems.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] In particular, the problem is that when an exonuclease hydrolyzes the phosphodiester bonds between nucleotides in DNA, the subsequently released nucleotide is not necessarily guaranteed to directly move into, say, a nearby alpha-hemolysin nanopore.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] In 2009, one idea has been to attach the exonuclease to the nanopore, perhaps through biotinylation to the beta barrel hemolysin.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] The central pore of the protein may be lined with charged residues arranged so that the positive and negative charges appear on opposite sides of the pore.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/nanopore-sequencing] However, this mechanism is primarily discriminatory and does not constitute a mechanism to guide nucleotides down some particular path.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] The principle of pyrosequencing was first described in 1993 by P.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] The technique combines solid phase sequencing, and use of streptavidin-coated magnetic beads, a recombinant DNA polymerase lacking 3´-to-5´exonuclease activity (proof-reading), and luminescence detection of inorganic pyrophosphate using the firefly luciferase enzyme.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] The intensity of the light determines if 0, 1, or more nucleotides have been incorporated, thus showing how many complementary nucleotides are present on the template strand.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] The nucleotide mixture is removed before a next nucleotide mixture is added, and the process is repeated for each of the four nucleotides, until the DNA sequence of the single stranded template is determined.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] A second solution-based method for pyrosequencing was described in 1998 by Mostafa Ronaghi, [Mathias Uhlen], and Pål Nyren.In this alternative method, an additional enzyme, apyrase, is introduced to remove nucleotides that are not incorporated by the DNA polymerase.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] This enables the enzyme mixture— DNA polymerase, luciferase, and apyrase—to be added when sequencing is initiated, and kept in the reaction solution throughout the procedure (thus enabling easier automation).
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] An automated instrument based on this principle was introduced to the market the following year by the company Pyrosequencing.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] A third variant, a microfluidic pyrosequencing method, was described in 2005 by an industrial research team led by Jonathan Rothberg, at the company 454 Life Sciences.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] This alternative approach for pyrosequencing was based on the original principle of attaching the DNA to be sequenced to a solid support; Rothberg and co-workers demonstrated that sequencing could be performed in a highly parallel manner using a microfabrication and microarrays.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] This allowed high-throughput DNA sequencing, and an automated instrument was introduced to the market.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] This first next generation sequencing instrument initiated a new era in genomics research, and to rapidly falling prices for DNA sequencing, allowing affordable whole genome sequencing.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] "Sequencing by synthesis" involves taking a single strand of the DNA to be sequenced and then synthesizing its complementary strand enzymatically.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] The pyrosequencing method is based on detecting the activity of DNA polymerase (a DNA synthesizing enzyme) with another chemoluminescent enzyme.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] Essentially, the method allows sequencing a single strand of DNA by synthesizing the complementary strand along it, one base pair at a time, and detecting which base was actually added at each step.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] The template DNA is immobile, and solutions of A, C, G, and T nucleotides are sequentially added and removed from the reaction.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] Light is produced only when the nucleotide solution complements the first unpaired base of the template.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] The sequence of solutions which produce chemiluminescent signals allows the determination of the sequence of the template.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] For the solution-based version of pyrosequencing, the single-strand DNA (ssDNA) template is hybridized to a sequencing primer and incubated with the enzymes DNA polymerase, ATP sulfurylase, luciferase and apyrase, and with the substrates adenosine 5´ phosphosulfate (APS) and luciferin.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] where PPi is pyrophosphate, APS is adenosine 5-phosphosulfate, ATP is adenosine triphosphate, O2 is dioxygen, AMP is adenosine monophosphate, CO2 is carbon dioxide, and hv is light.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] Currently, a limitation of the method is that the lengths of individual reads of DNA sequence are in the neighborhood of 300-500 nucleotides, shorter than the 800-1000 obtainable with chain termination methods (e.g.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] This can make the process of genome assembly more difficult, particularly for sequences containing a large amount of repetitive DNA.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] Also, lack of a proof-reading activity limits accuracy of this method.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] Pyrosequencing AB, a company based in Uppsala, Sweden, was founded with venture capital provided by HealthCap in order to commercialize machinery and reagents for sequencing short stretches of DNA using the pyrosequencing technique.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] Pyrosequencing AB was listed on the Stockholm Stock Exchange in 1999.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] When Pyrosequencing AB acquired Biotage LLC, a U.S.-based company, and other companies, in 2003, the company was renamed Biotage AB.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] The pyrosequencing and other biomedical units of Biotage AB were sold to Qiagen in 2008.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] The pyrosequencing technology was licensed to 454 Life Sciences.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] 454 developed an array-based pyrosequencing technology that emerged as a platform for large-scale DNA sequencing, including genome sequencing and metagenomics.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] Roche acquired 454 Life Sciences, and announced the discontinuation of the 454 sequencing platform in 2013.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/pyrosequencing] The 454 sequencing platform was replaced, in part, by Illumina dye sequencing, and by Applied Biosystems sequencing products.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] In DNA sequencing, a **read** is an inferred sequence of base pairs (or base pair probabilities) corresponding to all or part of a single DNA fragment.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] A typical sequencing experiment involves fragmentation of the genome into millions of molecules, which are size-selected and ligated to adapters.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] The set of fragments is referred to as a sequencing library, which is sequenced to produce a set of reads.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Sequencing technologies vary in the length of reads produced.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Reads of length 20-40 base pairs (bp) are referred to as ultra-short.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Typical sequencers produce read lengths in the range of 100-500 bp.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] However, Pacific Biosciences platforms produce read lengths of approximately 1500 bp.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Read length is a factor which can affect the results of biological studies.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] For example, longer read lengths improve the resolution of *de novo* genome assembly and detection of structural variants.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] It is estimated that read lengths greater than 100 kilobases (kb) will be required for routine *de novo* human genome assembly.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Bioinformatic pipelines to analyze sequencing data usually take into account read lengths.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] A genome is the complete genetic information of an organism or a cell.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Single or double stranded nucleic acids store this information in a linear or in a circular sequence.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] To precisely determine this sequence, over time more efficient technologies with increased accuracy, throughput and sequencing speed have been developed.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Sanger and Maxam-Gilbert sequencing technologies were classified as the First Generation Sequencing Technology who initiated the field of DNA sequencing with their publication in 1977.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] First Generation Sequencing typically has read lengths of 400 to 900 base pairs.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] In 2005 Roche’s 454 technology introduced new sequencing technology that was capable of high throughput at low cost.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] This and similar technologies came to be known as Second Generation Sequencing or Next Generation Sequencing (NGS).
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] One of the hallmarks of NSG is short sequence reads.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] NGS methods may sequence millions to billions of reads in a single run, and the time it takes to create GigaBase-sized reads is only a few days or hours, making it superior to first-generation sequencing techniques like Sanger sequencing.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] All NSG techniques produce short reads, i.e.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] 80–200 bases, as opposed to longer length reads produced by Sanger sequencing.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Beginning in the 2010s, revolutionary new technologies ushered in the Third-Generation Sequencing era (TGS).
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] TGS is a term used to describe methods that are capable of sequencing single DNA molecules without amplification.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] While Sanger and SRS techniques can only produce read lengths of one kilobase pair, third-generation sequencing technologies can produce read lengths of 5 to 30 kilobase pairs.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] The longest read length ever generated by a third-generation sequencing technology is 2 million base pairs.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Historically, only one individual per species was addressed due to time and expense constraints, and its sequence served as the species' "reference" genome.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] These reference genomes can be used to guide resequencing efforts in the same species by serving as a read mapping template.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Read mapping is the process to align NGS reads on a reference genome.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Any NGS application, such as genome variation calling, transcriptome analysis, transcription factor binding site calling, epigenetic mark calling, metagenomics, and so on, requires read mapping.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] The performance of these applications is influenced by accurate alignment.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Furthermore, because the number of reads is so large, the mapping process must be efficient.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] There are different methods used to align reads on reference genome depending on how many mismatches and indels are being allowed.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Roughly speaking, the methods can be divided into two categories: the seed-and-extension approach and the filtering approach.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Many short read aligners use the seed-and-extend strategy, such as BWA-SW, Bowtie 2, BatAlign, LAST, Cushaw2, BWA-MEM, etc.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] A filter-based approach is used by a number of methods like SeqAlto, GEM, MASAI etc.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] In genomics, reassembling genomes by DNA sequencing is a significant challenge.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] The retrieved reads span the entire genome uniformly due to random sampling.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Reads are stitched together computationally to reconstruct the genome.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] This process is known as de novo genome assembly.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] I Sanger sequencing has larger read length compared to NGS.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Two assemblers were developed for assembling Sanger sequencing reads - the OLC assembler Celera and the de Bruijn graph assembler Euler.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] These two methods were used to put together our human reference genome.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] However, since Sanger sequencing is low throughput and expensive, only a few genomes are assembled with Sanger sequencing.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Second-generation sequencing reads are short, and these sequencing techniques can efficiently and cost-effectively sequence hundreds of millions of reads.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] For rebuilding genomes from short sequences, some custom genome assemblers have been built.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Their success spawned several de novo genome assembly projects.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Although this method is cost-effective, the reads are short and the repeat sections are long, resulting in fragmented genomes.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] We now have very long reads (of 10,000 bp) thanks to the arrival of third-generation sequencing.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Long reads are capable of resolving the ordering of repeat regions, although they have a high error rate (15–18%).
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] To correct errors in third-generation sequencing reads, a number of computational methods have been devised.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Assembling with short reads and assembling with long reads have different advantages and disadvantages owing to error rates and ease of assembly.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Sometimes a hybrid method is preferred, and short reads and long reads are combined to get better result.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] There are two approaches, the first one is using mate-pair reads and long reads to improve the assembly from the short reads.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Second approach is using short reads to correct the errors in long reads.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Second-generation sequencing generates short reads (of length < 300bp) and these are highly accurate (sequencing error rate equals ~1%).
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Short read sequencing technologies have made sequencing much easier, a lot faster and much cheaper than Sanger sequencing.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] The August 2019 report from the National Human Genome Research Institute put the cost of sequencing a complete human genome at $942.00 United States dollars (USD).
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] The inability to sequence lengthy sections of DNA is a drawback shared by all second-generation sequencing technology.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] To use NGS to sequence a big genome like human DNA, the DNA must be fragmented and amplified in clones ranging from 75 to 400 base pairs, that is why NGS is also known as "shortread sequencing" (SRS).
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] After sequencing short reads, it then becomes a computational problem and many computer programs and techniques have been developed to assemble the random clones into a contiguous sequence.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] A necessary step in SRS is polymerase chain reaction which causes preferential amplification of repetitive DNA.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] SRS also fails to generate sufficient overlap sequence from the DNA fragments.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] This constitutes a major challenge for de novo sequencing of a highly complex and repetitive genome like the human genome.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Another challenge with SRS is the detection of large sequence changes, which is a major roadblock to studying structural variations.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] The third-generation sequencing sequences long reads and is often referred to as long read sequencing (LRS).
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] LRS technologies are capable of sequencing single DNA molecules without amplification.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] The availability of long reads constitutes a great advantage, because it is often difficult to generate long continuous consensus sequence using NGS because of the difficulty of detecting overlaps between NGS short reads, thus impacting the overall quality of assembly.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] LRS has been shown to considerably improve the quality of genome assemblies in several studies.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Another advantage of LRS over NGS is that it provides the simultaneous capability of characterizing a variety of epigenetic marks along with DNA sequencing.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Major challenge of LRS is accuracy and cost.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/read-biology] Though with LRS is improving fast in those areas too.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] The DNA sequencing is done on a chip that contains many ZMWs.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] Inside each ZMW, a single active DNA polymerase with a single molecule of single stranded DNA template is immobilized to the bottom through which light can penetrate and create a visualization chamber that allows monitoring of the activity of the DNA polymerase at a single molecule level.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] The signal from a phospho-linked nucleotide incorporated by the DNA polymerase is detected as the DNA synthesis proceeds which results in the DNA sequencing in real time.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] To prepare the library, DNA fragments are put into a circular form using hairpin adapter ligations.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] For each of the nucleotide bases, there is a corresponding fluorescent dye molecule that enables the detector to identify the base being incorporated by the DNA polymerase as it performs the DNA synthesis.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] The fluorescent dye molecule is attached to the phosphate chain of the nucleotide.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] When the nucleotide is incorporated by the DNA polymerase, the fluorescent dye is cleaved off with the phosphate chain as a part of a natural DNA synthesis process during which a phosphodiester bond is created to elongate the DNA chain.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] The cleaved fluorescent dye molecule then diffuses out of the detection volume so that the fluorescent signal is no longer detected.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] The zero-mode waveguide (ZMW) is a nanophotonic confinement structure that consists of a circular hole in an aluminum cladding film deposited on a clear silica substrate.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] The ZMW holes are ~70 nm in diameter and ~100 nm in depth.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] Due to the behavior of light when it travels through a small aperture, the optical field decays exponentially inside the chamber.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] The observation volume within an illuminated ZMW is ~20 zeptoliters (20 X 10−21 liters).
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] The observation volume being so low eliminates background fluorescence from the free, unincorporated fluorescent nucleotides present in the solution.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] Within this volume, the activity of DNA polymerase incorporating a single nucleotide can be readily detected where each nucleotide is a separate color.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] Sequencing performance can be measured in read length, accuracy, and total throughput per experiment.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] PacBio sequencing systems using ZMWs have the advantage of long read lengths, although error rates are on the order of 5-15% and sample throughput is lower than Illumina sequencing platforms.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] On 19 Sep 2018, Pacific Biosciences [PacBio] released the Sequel 6.0 chemistry, synchronizing the chemistry version with the software version.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] Performance is contrasted for large-insert libraries with high molecular weight DNA versus shorter-insert libraries below ~15,000 bases in length.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] For larger templates average read lengths are up to 30,000 bases.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] For shorter-insert libraries, average read length are up to 100,000 bases while reading the same molecule in a circle several times.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] The latter shorter-insert libraries then yield up to 50 billion bases from a single SMRT Cell.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] Pacific Biosciences (PacBio) commercialized SMRT sequencing in 2011, after releasing a beta version of its RS instrument in late 2010.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] At commercialization, read length had a normal distribution with a mean of about 1100 bases.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] A new chemistry kit released in early 2012 increased the sequencer's read length; an early customer of the chemistry cited mean read lengths of 2500 to 2900 bases.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] The XL chemistry kit released in late 2012 increased average read length to more than 4300 bases.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] On August 21, 2013, PacBio released a new DNA polymerase Binding Kit P4.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] This P4 enzyme has average read lengths of more than 4,300 bases when paired with the C2 sequencing chemistry and more than 5,000 bases when paired with the XL chemistry.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] The enzyme’s accuracy is similar to C2, reaching QV50 between 30X and 40X coverage.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] The resulting P4 attributes provided higher-quality assemblies using fewer SMRT Cells and with improved variant calling.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] When coupled with input DNA size selection (using an electrophoresis instrument such as BluePippin) yields average read length over 7 kilobases.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] On October 3, 2013, PacBio released new reagent combination for PacBio RS II, the P5 DNA polymerase with C3 chemistry (P5-C3).
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] Together, they extend sequencing read lengths to an average of approximately 8,500 bases, with the longest reads exceeding 30,000 bases.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] Throughput per SMRT cell is around 500 million bases demonstrated by sequencing results from the CHM1 cell line.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] On October 15, 2014, PacBio announced the release of new chemistry P6-C4 for the RS II system, which represents the company's 6th generation of polymerase and 4th generation chemistry--further extending the average read length to 10,000 - 15,000 bases, with the longest reads exceeding 40,000 bases.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] The throughput with the new chemistry was estimated between 500 million to 1 billion bases per SMRT Cell, depending on the sample being sequenced.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] This was the final version of chemistry released for the RS instrument.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] Throughput per experiment for the technology is both influenced by the read length of DNA molecules sequenced as well as total multiplex of a SMRT Cell.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] The prototype of the SMRT Cell contained about 3000 ZMW holes that allowed parallelized DNA sequencing.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] At commercialization, the SMRT Cells were each patterned with 150,000 ZMW holes that were read in two sets of 75,000.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] In April 2013, the company released a new version of the sequencer called the "PacBio RS II" that uses all 150,000 ZMW holes concurrently, doubling the throughput per experiment.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] The highest throughput mode in November 2013 used P5 binding, C3 chemistry, BluePippin size selection, and a PacBio RS II officially yielded 350 million bases per SMRT Cell though a human *de novo* data set released with the chemistry averaging 500 million bases per SMRT Cell.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] Throughput varies based on the type of sample being sequenced.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] With the introduction of P6-C4 chemistry typical throughput per SMRT Cell increased to 500 million bases to 1 billion bases.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] In September 2015, the company announced the launch of a new sequencing instrument, the Sequel System, that increased capacity to 1 million ZMW holes.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] With the Sequel instrument initial read lengths were comparable to the RS, then later chemistry releases increased read length.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] On January 23, 2017, the V2 chemistry was released.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] It increased average read lengths to between 10,000 and 18,000 bases.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] On March 8, 2018, the 2.1 chemistry was released.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] It increased average read length to 20,000 bases and half of all reads above 30,000 bases in length.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] Yield per SMRT Cell increased to 10 or 20 billion bases, for either large-insert libraries or shorter-insert (e.g. amplicon) libraries respectively.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] On 19 September 2018, the company announced the Sequel 6.0 chemistry with average read lengths increased to 100,000 bases for shorter-insert libraries and 30,000 for longer-insert libraries.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] SMRT Cell yield increased up to 50 billion bases for shorter-insert libraries.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] In April 2019 the company released a new SMRT Cell with eight million ZMWs, increasing the expected throughput per SMRT Cell by a factor of eight.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] Early access customers in March 2019 reported throughput over 58 customer run cells of 250 GB of raw yield per cell with templates about 15 kb in length, and 67.4 GB yield per cell with templates in higher weight molecules.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] System performance is now reported in either high-molecular-weight continuous long reads or in pre-corrected HiFi (also known as Circular Consensus Sequence (CCS)) reads.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] For high-molecular-weight reads roughly half of all reads are longer than 50 kb in length.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] The HiFi performance includes corrected bases with quality above Phred score Q20, using repeated amplicon passes for correction.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] These take amplicons up to 20kb in length.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] Single-molecule real-time sequencing may be applicable for a broad range of genomics research.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] For *de novo* genome sequencing, read lengths from the single-molecule real-time sequencing are comparable to or greater than that from the Sanger sequencing method based on dideoxynucleotide chain termination.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] The longer read length allows *de novo* genome sequencing and easier genome assemblies.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] Scientists are also using single-molecule real-time sequencing in hybrid assemblies for de novo genomes to combine short-read sequence data with long-read sequence data.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] In 2012, several peer-reviewed publications were released demonstrating the automated finishing of bacterial genomes, including one paper that updated the Celera Assembler with a pipeline for genome finishing using long SMRT sequencing reads.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] In 2013, scientists estimated that long-read sequencing could be used to fully assemble and finish the majority of bacterial and archaeal genomes.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] The same DNA molecule can be resequenced independently by creating the circular DNA template and utilizing a strand displacing enzyme that separates the newly synthesized DNA strand from the template.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] In August 2012, scientists from the Broad Institute published an evaluation of SMRT sequencing for SNP calling.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] The dynamics of polymerase can indicate whether a base is methylated.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] Scientists demonstrated the use of single-molecule real-time sequencing for detecting methylation and other base modifications.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] In 2012 a team of scientists used SMRT sequencing to generate the full methylomes of six bacteria.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] In November 2012, scientists published a report on genome-wide methylation of an outbreak strain of E. coli.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] Long reads make it possible to sequence full gene isoforms, including the 5' and 3' ends.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] This type of sequencing is useful to capture isoforms and splice variants.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] SMRT sequencing has several applications in reproductive medical genetics research when investigating families with suspected parental gonadal mosaicism.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] Long reads enable haplotype phasing in patients to investigate parent-of-origin of mutations.
[src:next-gen-sequencing/single-molecule-real-time-sequencing] Deep sequencing enables determination of allele frequencies in sperm cells, of relevance for estimation of recurrence risk for future affected offspring.
